<section id="fb2">
  <p class="feedbacktext">1B. 'Many' is for countable nouns only. Money is an uncountable noun.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb5">
  <p class="feedbacktext">2A. 'Few' is for countable nouns only. Time is uncountable noun.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb8">
  <p class="feedbacktext">2D. 'Number' suits only countable nouns. Time is an uncountable noun.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb10">
  <p class="feedbacktext">3B. 'Least' is for uncountable nouns, unless it is used in the expression 'least number of'.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb13">
  <p class="feedbacktext">4A. 'Much' cannot be used in this way with countable nouns such as 'days'.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb17">
  <p class="feedbacktext">5A. 'Less' is for uncountable nouns.</p>
</section>

<section id="fb19">
  <p class="feedbacktext">5C. A 'quantity of residents' is not natural English usage.</p>
</section>

<section id="examtips">
  <p class="popuptext">In order to describe the information shown in tables and charts you will need to use language for describing and comparing quantities. You must decide whether the figures refer to countable or uncountable nouns and use appropriate quantifiers (many, much, little, few, etc.).
  </p>
</section>

